ğŸŒ What is CORS? (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing)
CORS stands for Cross-Origin Resource Sharing.
Itâ€™s a security feature built into web browsers that controls how a webpage (frontend) can request data from a different domain (backend).
ğŸ’¡ In simple words:
Imagine your React app is running on
â¡ï¸ http://localhost:5173
and your backend API (Node.js server) is running on
â¡ï¸ http://localhost:5000.
When your React app tries to fetch data from the backend, the browser says:

â€œWait! This request is coming from a different origin. Should I allow it or block it?â€

By default, the browser blocks it â€” to protect users from malicious websites trying to access sensitive data.
To fix this, we must tell our backend server:

â€œHey browser, itâ€™s safe to allow requests from my frontend!â€

And thatâ€™s where CORS setup comes in.

âš™ï¸ When Youâ€™ll Face This Issue
Youâ€™ll usually see an error like this in the console:
Access to fetch at 'http://localhost:5000/api/data' from origin 'http://localhost:5173' has been blocked by CORS policy.

This means the backend didnâ€™t allow your frontend to connect.

âœ… How to Fix It (CORS Setup Example)
Hereâ€™s a simple Node.js + Express example showing how to fix CORS properly.
ğŸ§© Backend Code (server.js)
import express from "express";
import cors from "cors";

const app = express();

// âœ… Enable CORS for all domains (during development)
app.use(cors());

// OR (Better) Allow specific frontend origin
// app.use(cors({ origin: "http://localhost:5173" }));

app.get("/api/data", (req, res) => {
  res.json({ message: "Hello from backend!" });
});

app.listen(5000, () => {
  console.log("Server running on http://localhost:5000");
});

ğŸ§  What this does:


import cors from "cors" â†’ Imports the CORS package.


app.use(cors()) â†’ Enables CORS for all incoming requests.


You can also restrict it to a specific frontend URL for better security:
app.use(cors({ origin: "http://localhost:5173" }));

This means: â€œOnly allow my React app to make requests to this backend.â€



ğŸ’» Frontend Code (React Example)
import axios from "axios";

function App() {
  const fetchData = async () => {
    const response = await axios.get("http://localhost:5000/api/data");
    console.log(response.data);
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <button onClick={fetchData}>Get Data</button>
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;

When you click the button, the data from your backend will load without any CORS error âœ….

ğŸ§¾ Summary


CORS protects browsers from unsafe data sharing.


Youâ€™ll face CORS issues when frontend and backend run on different domains or ports.


Fix by enabling CORS in the backend server using the cors package.


Always restrict access in production (donâ€™t allow â€œ*â€ for all origins).



